[normal]1. [bold]Introduction[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]1.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]I founded the See Me Save Me campaign after my sister Eilidh Cairns, 
[normal]a fit and experienced cyclist of 
[normal]30yrs, was run down from behind by a fully laden tipper truck in Notting Hill Gate as she cycled to work on 5
[normal]th
[normal] February 2009
[normal];
[normal] and 
[normal]as 
[normal]it 
[normal]became apparent how frequently cyclists and 
[normal]pedestrians
[normal] were being killed and seriously injured by HGVs
[normal];
[normal] and how little preventative action
[normal],
[normal] or even acknowledgement
[normal],
[normal] was
[normal] given by industry, government 
[normal]or the legal system to such systematic failure and loss.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In the majority of cases where a cyclist is killed the driver claims they did not see them. In the majority of cases there is no prosecution. See Me Save Me campaigns for elimination of blind spots in HGVs and for greater visibility for cyclists in the j
[normal]ustice system.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.3
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]I trained as a civil engineer and have worked in the construction industry for 20 years
[normal], currently as an independent sustainability advisor
[normal]. I am a member of the Institution of Civil Engineers
[normal] 
[normal](ICE) 
[normal]and s
[normal]it on its
[normal] national Cycle Working 
[normal]Group and 
[normal]as such 
[normal]repres
[normal]ent the ICE on the TfL 
[normal]construction logistics 
[normal]industry 
[normal]working group currently drafting an industry standard to manage work related road risk to vulnerable road users (VRU). 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.4
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
